        "### 1. What happens to the decision boundary as K increases?\n",
        "\n",
        "As **K increases, the boundary becomes smoother.** * **Small K (e.g., k=1):** The boundary is jagged and follows the individual data points very closely, capturing \"noise.\"\n",
        "\n",
        "* **Large K (e.g., k=10):** The boundary simplifies, ignoring small outliers to show the broader trend.\n",
        "\n",
        "### 2. Which K value seems to generalize better without overfitting?\n",
        "\n",
        "**K=5 or K=10** generally generalize better.\n",
        "\n",
        "* **K=1** is \"overfitting\"—it memorizes the exact training data, which means it might fail when it sees new, unseen data.\n",
        "* **K=10** is more stable and \"generalized,\" making it more reliable for real-world predictions.\n",
        "\n",
        "### 3. Try changing the metric to 'manhattan'—how does the boundary change?\n",
        "\n",
        "Changing the metric to **manhattan** makes the decision boundaries look **more angular or \"blocky.\"**\n",
        "\n",
        "* Because Manhattan distance measures distance along a grid (like walking city blocks) rather than a straight line (Euclidean), the \"influence zones\" of the data points align more with the horizontal and vertical axes.\n",
        "\n"
